      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <ab><lb n="01"/>siddha<unclear>ṁ</unclear><!--
Siddham is written vertically (characters one below the other, but in standard orientation) on the left margin. 'si' is before and a hair above the beginning of line 2; 'ddha' is before and slightly above the beginning of line 3. I see no anusvāra in the facsimile.
--></ab>
        <lg met="sragdharā" n="1">
          <l n="a"><lb n="1"/>yasyopasthāna-bhūmir nr̥pati-śata-śiraḥ-pāta-vāt-āvadhūtā<!--
There is a short, straight horizontal mark after the visarga of śiraḥ. As Bhandarkar (1981:307n3) notes, this is probably a slip of the chisel rather than a punctuation mark.
--></l>
          <l n="b"><lb n="2"/>guptānāṁ va<sic>n</sic>śa-jasya pravisr̥ta-yaśasas tasya sarvvottamarddheḥ</l>
          <l n="c"><lb n="3"/>rājye śakropamasya kṣitipa-śata-pateḥ skandaguptasya śānte</l>
          <l n="d"><lb n="4"/>varṣe ttri<sic>n</sic>śad-daśaikottaraka-śatatame jyeṣṭha-māsi prapanne|<!--
The daṇḍa is a horizontal dash curving slightly up in the middle. Note the late caesura.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="sragdharā" n="2">
          <l n="a"><lb n="5"/>khyāte smin grāma-ratne kakubha Iti janais sādhu-saṁsarga-pūte|<!--
The unnecessary daṇḍa may be just a space filler, or may have been engraved in a sort of automatism after a legitimate daṇḍa at the end of the previous line.
--></l>
          <l n="b"><lb n="6"/>puttro yas somilasya pracura-guṇa-nidher bhaṭṭisomo mahāt<unclear>m</unclear>ā</l>
          <l n="c"><lb n="7"/>tat-sūnū rudrasoma<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied> pr̥thula-mati-yaśā vyāghra Ity anya-saṁjño|</l>
          <l n="d"><lb n="8"/>madras tasyātmajo bhūd dvija-guru-yatiṣu prāyaśaḥ prītimān yaḥ|</l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="sragdharā" n="3">
          <l n="a"><lb n="9"/>puṇya-skandhaṁ sa cakkre jagad idam akhilaṁ saṁsarad vīkṣya bhīto</l>
          <l n="b"><lb n="10"/>śreyortthaṁ bhūta-bhūtyai pathi niyamavatām arhatām ādi-kartt<choice>
              <sic>r̥</sic>
              <corr>r̥̄</corr>
            </choice>N<!--
Salomon_1998:274 says the reading is actually viyamavatām (emending to ni°). The inked rubbing from CII3rev does look like vi; it is clearly ni on Indraji's impression (which may have been retouched). I have no other image; even on the inked rubbing, the character doesn't look quite like the va of vatām, and there is a slight extension toward the right that may well be the trace of the longer tail visible in Indraji's copy.
--><!--
kartt{{!r̥!}{=r̥̄=}}N[+|] corrected in May 2015, was karttr̥īn in first100.
--><!--
The halanta N is a slightly simplified, cursive form; the essence of its difference from na is that this lacks a headmark, beginning instead with a smooth curve from the left.
--></l>
          <l n="c"><lb n="11"/>pañcendrā<choice>
              <sic>ṁ</sic>
              <corr>n</corr>
            </choice> sthāpayitvā dharaṇidhara-mayān sannikhātas tato yaM<!--
The final m looks like a simplified, cursive, but full-sized ma character.
--></l>
          <l n="d"><lb n="12"/>śaila-stambhaḥ sucārur giri-vara-śikharāgropamaḥ kīrtti-karttā<!--
Note the early second caesura.
--></l>
        </lg>
